{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_tango_ver02/data/sn84026749/100492672/1908062601/0075.xml":{"full_text":"LAGHANGES ADJOURN\nIN THE AFTERNOON\nSpeculation Ceases Out of\nRespect to Grover\nCleveland.\nMARKET IS DULL\nAND PRICES FIRM\nWall Street Hopeful of Good\nCrops, Better Business, and\nReturn of Prosperity.\n\n\n\nNEW YORK, June 26.\u2014The stock and\nproduce exchanges of the country gen\nerally closed at 1 o'clock today, out\nof respect to the memory of Grover\nCleveland. This did not include th2\ncotton exchanges of New York and\nNew Orleans, it being July notice day\nand not possible for either to join in\nhalf-day adjournment.\n\np\u2014\n_.-\n\n\nThe stock market opened strong in\nthe main and in many instances higher\nthan last night's closing. The market\nat the start was quite irregular, but\nafter a short time steadied, and before\nthe end ot) the short session several\nstocks had {added fractional or whole\npoint gains to the prices of yesterday.\n\nAt the start declines and advances\nwere fractional and Seg evenly di\nvided throughout the list! Amalgamated\nand Anaconda were heavy at the open\ning, the former losing and the latter\n1,. Amalgamated subsequently rallied\n3. American Locomotive was strong\nand advanced 1\u00a2 point, as did Westing\nhouse. At the end of the first half\nhour of trading, the market became\ndull, but with nearly all issues showing\nfractional gains. Erie, 1st preferred,\nrose 1 points, while the common de\nclined 1k.\nOwing to the report that contracts\nhad been signed with bankers for the\npayment of interest and maturing obli\ngations of the St. Louis and San Fran\ncisco railway company, that stock rose\n1 point to 22%. As the recent raids on\nRock Island securities were partly based\non the uncertainty cf these payments,\nannouncement that they would be met\nstrengthened Rock Island.\nDisquieting news came by cable from\nJ.ondon that there had been a break\nof one point in Rio Tintos in that mar\nket and had a weakening effect upon\nthe Coppers here and in Boston. Amal\ngamated opened half a point lower than\nlast night, In sympathy with the rews,\nbut gained stout fractions as the trad\ning proceeded, and closed well above\nthe decline of the morning.\nThe Steel stocks were firm and active.\nSmelters opened ex-dividend about \u00a71 a\nshare below last night's closing, was\nquite active and gained half a point.\nOne of the features of the market was\nthe high opening of Manhattan Eie\nvated, due to the adjustment of several\nmatters that have affected the local\ntraction shares adversely for several\ndays.\nUnion Pacific, Smelters, and Reading\nwere the leaders in a market, whick\nwas almost the counterpart of yester\n\u00e9ay, marked by professional trading,\nmall business and gradually rising\nprices.\nNews from the business world con\ntiniues hopeful, and the attention of\nVall Street is centered upon the prom\nise of good crops of all kinds. The ir\npression is that with a continunatior\nof the conditions that have prevailed\nthe wheat, cotton, and corn should com\nin\u00bb harvest and picking with yields tha\nwill equal. if not surpass, the produc\ntion of other years. The fiuct is recog\nnized that with good crops the volume\nof business on before the stringency of\nJas: vear -~annot long be delayed, and\nthat the country, chastened by panic.\nand with finances newly adjusted will\n\u00a2pter upon a new period of prosperity.\nThis is the hope of Wall Street,\nstrengthened as day follows day of good\nweather over the vast reaches of agri\ncultural operations on the Western con\ntinent.\nMembers\nR=ilroad news today, though not as\ncheering as could have been hoped, was\nnot without itg encouraging features.\nNew Jersey Central in its last report\nshows a surplus of $67,826 for the month\nof May, without making deductions for\nrenewais. As compared with last year,\nthis is not a very favorable showing, but\nWall Street has had so many knocks\nthis year that it catches at smaller\nthings than it once did, and the report\nis spoken of as good under the circum\nstances.\n\nIn a similar manner, the report of the\nAmerican Car and Foundry Company\nmade public yesterday, gives most spec\nulators hope. The report covered the\nfiscal year ended April 30, and showed\nthat the company had disbursed larger\nd:vidends than ever before in its his\ntory, though its year\u2019s earnings had\nfallen off something over $500,000. The\nreport is interpreted to mean that the\ncompany i. till making money and that\nits management shows that it is in saf\u00a2\nhands ard is capable of coming out with\na surplus at the end of the year.\nThese indications show the more hope\nful mood into which the financial and\nspeculative community has entered, and\nit wonld appear that about all that is\nnow needed is for Wall Street to get rid\nof its unwonted timidity to start the\nstock market on a long and healthy bul\nmovement.\nji.\nFRICES FOR TODAY ON\nNEW YORK EXCHANGE\n(Quotations furnished by W. B. Hibbs\nCc.. bankers and brokers, Hibbs Bullding,\nmembers New York Stock Exchange, Wash\nington Stock Exchange and Chicago Board of\nea Ades\n\n\nET TT TT\nOpen.High: Low. 1:20.\nAmalgamated Cop... Boy 6brs 60% Godg\nAm. Can. Co., pr... Haly 03% 53 53%\nAm. Car Foun... 24a 4s 33a 33%\nAna. Locomeotive..... 48 4%, 47% Wy\nAm. Locomo.; pfd....102 102 102 12\nsam. Smelting iv Tol, T4Rg THY\nAN. BUBHAE. ..ssusssn wn a 124% 12434 1240\nAncona. ....ud renee i 4 41% 42\nAl. Top. &S. Fe...... 813% S13 $1 S135\nAt. Top. 8S. F., pfd 94 94 94 Yi\nBaltimore Ohijo.... 55% 86's \u00a33 ia\nErooklyn Rapid Ti... 4% 47 46%\nCanadian Pac.......... 1599 159% Todades\nChes. Ohio...... eee 39% 10 3s Ww\nChi GC. W.ouvannsoins 69 63% 63%; 63\na\nChi, Mil. St. P....132% 133% 13214 133%\nChi., M. St. P. pf..150 150 150 150\nA\nChicago N. W...... 14976 150% 14975 150%\nCol. Southern......... 30 301g 30 30%\nCon. Gas .....dvivees 123 12335 122 123%\nCorn Producets........ 163, 163; 163; 16%\nDistillers Securities... 34 341% 34\nErie\u2019 fom... asap 3\u00b0 9% 1 19%\nErie, lst pf.....ecasie BY, 38% 35% Ws\n\u00a5Erie, 24 preferred..... 2% HM 4 2M\nGeneral Electric....... 134 134\u00b0 134 134\n\n\n\na\n93.00\nGreat Northern Ore.. 59 58 581 58\nGreat Northern, pfd..130 131 130 131\nIllinois Central........ 127 12834 127 128%\nInter. Metropolitan... 103, BT 103g 10%\nInter. Metropol., pid. 281, 28% 281; 28%\nLouisville Nash....104% 104% 100% 104%\n\n\nj Bouse renters in this city. A\nmake\n\nMo., K. Tex. com. 2iig 27% ry\nM., K.&7T., pfd...... 3 39\nMS P.&\u00a35. 8. M....108 108 168\nMissouri Pacific....... \u00a315 97% H's\nNational Biscuit Co.. 84 4 $4\nNational Lead......... 64% 643% 64%\n\n\n\nByfszeatons\n\nRs\nNX. Y. Air Brake...... 66i; 662\nNe York Central, 1015 02 101%\nN.\u00a5X..On. West....\nNorthern Pacifici... ress\na\nLOGAL EXGrANGE\nADJOURNS TODAY\nWashington Brokers Sus\npend Business in Memory\nof Grover Cleveland.\nAt the meeting of the Washington\nStock Exchange today it was voted to\nadjourn the session in respect to the\nmemory of Grover Cleveland.\n\ni\nMotion t> that effect was made by\nAlbion K. Parris, who made a brief\nspeech unon the esteem in which the\nvenerable ex-President, who recently\ndied in Princeton, was held by the\nAmerican people. Mr. Parris called at\ntention to the fact tnat the exchanges\nof Nev. York, Chicago, and other clties\nhad voted to adjourn at 1 o'clock, and\nhe thought it meet that in Wash\nington, wher a great part of the pub\nlic life of Mr. Cleveland had been spent,\nsimilar action should be taken.\nrT\n\nMr. Parris said there could be but one\nopinion as to the high character of Mr,\nCleveland. Ife had stood for what he\nunderstood to be right always. Since\nhis retirement to Princeton he had set\nfor his countrymen a noble example of\ndignified and patriotic life, and Mr.\nParris thought that as business men\nthey should suspend business for thea\nday out of respect to the memory of\ns0 good a man, and so great a states\nman.\nThe motion was unanimously passed,\nand no business was transacted of a\nformal nature. The exchange will meet\nas usual tomorrow.\nOpen. High. Low. 1:30\n12036 121\n\u201cEx. dividend, 1 per cent.\nBean. RR. PBaaecerrrinan 12032 121\nPressed Steel Car.... 27% 2% 21% 27%\nReading  ......icaiaa 11% 11255 111% TEN\nRep. Iron and Steel.. 17 17\nRUock Island: com... 1635 1614 15%\nRcck Island pfd...... 29%, 30%, 201, 30\nSloss-Shefficld Steel. 48 50% 49 5034\nSL&ESF.24pfd.. 22 2 2 2\nSouth Pae............. RG ST 86% ST%\nSouth Pac., pfd....... 11835 11945 119% 119%\nSouth RY... ones 167% 17% 16% 17%\nSouth Ry. pfd........ 40% 44 a3 uu\nTennessee Copper..... By 3B By 36\nT. 5t. ast. 19% 191% 19%, 1944\nT. St. L. W. pfd... 441; 443, 44, HV\nUnion IPA cesses snnsnosn S184, 145%: 144% 145%\nSeal... cues oy 37 373, Vy 37%\nU. 8. Steel, pfd....... 102% 10235 102 1023;\nUtah Copper....... S21 4% Fs 34%\nWabash, pfd........ veh 2% 27g\n\"West. -Union.....\u00bb..... 1% ble Hy 51%\nWest. Elec. Man. 56% 587s 552 56\nBOXDS.\nAm. Tob. \u00a3\u00a33....cenuns Qs Ns Np 92,\nAm Pah. $8 near 10422 104% 104% 10474\nBRT 48...0ncanuann 73 2% 27%\nInt. Met. fi2's......... 6515 65% 601 6%\nly Island 4's. 81 613; 61% 613\n8. Steel o's......... 951, 963 9\no> Con. 4's. 918g 913, 9155 9i\u00a5\n{Quotations furnished by E. F. Hutton\nCo., members New York Stock Exchange,\n1201 F street northwest\nOpen. High. Low. 1:30.\nBoston Col'd Cop..... 13 1135 11% 11%\nCumberland Ely...... Ms Ts 5%\nDominion Copper..... 133 1% 1% 15\nGoldfield Cons\u2019ted.... 57; 5% 56% 3%\nGreene Cananea....... 16 10g 10 10\nMicmac Gold Mi.n.... 23% 233 2% 24\nSi Xinley. Darragh... 79 $81 79\nNevada Consol........ 115% 11% 1185 115\u00a2\nNevada Pmeline. A ig 1% 1a M\nNevada Hal So 3 3 EA EM\nNipissin Th JP 7\nSe A TRA 600 600 600 600\nTri ont Peg fens semua 1% 13% 1% 135\nDAlSY  ......cccveuse. T 8 B\u00ae 95\nFlounbe Ll. ci 5% 3 fe\nConditions were encouraging in the\nlocal produce market this morning. Re\nceipts were liberal and an active de\nmand on all goods, especially fruits and\ngreen vegetables made prices favorable.\nMost summer goods arrived in better\nquantities than at any previous time\nand they wer\u00bb cheaper in consequence.\nWholesale prices are:\nEggs\u2014Nearby, fancy, {resh, Virginia, 16%sc;\nnearby, average, 15al6\u00a2c; W. Va., and 8S. W.\nVa., 15alfc; Tennessee, lial\u00e9e.\nCheese\u2014N. Y. State, factory, large, old.\n13%zaldc: flats, l4c; small, l4alfle; summer,\nlarge, lSalSc; summer, small, ifalse; fair to\nWestern factory, new choice\n\u201cale, fair to good. llc; Virginia, %c.\nlutter-\u2014~Cieamery, fancy, 24a%ec; Western,\nfirsts, 23al4c; seconds, Zazle; process,\nfancy, 21al2c; fair to good, 1%a20c; dairy,\nshoice, 17aise: good, 16\u00a2; store, packed. fresh,\nTive Poultry\u2014Chickens, spring, large 23a\n24c; small, 2l1al22c; hens, small, per lb., 13a\nase; large, per lb., 13%c; roosters, per Rin, dE;\ncucks, spring. large, per lb, Aas small,\np=r ib., 9c; geese, per ib., 7a8c; turkeys, toms,\n12; bens l4c; thin, loc; keais, per ib., 10c.\nmessed Poultry\u2014Turkeys, undrawn, hens,\n1b.., 15alc; average, undrawn, mixed, per\nto. 14c; thin, per ib., l\u00a2allc; young toms, l4c;\nola toms, 13c; chickens. spring. large, per\nIb., 21\u00a2; spring, smail, per 1b., 20a2lc; hens,\nchoice, per Ib., 1c; roosters, per 1b., \u00a5c;\nducks, l0alle; geese, per 1b., Salle.\nGreen Fruit\u2014Apples\u2014June, per bbl., $1.60a\n2.00; Cah'srnia, navels, per box, $3.50a4.50;\ngrape fruit, Florida, per box, $2.25a4.50;\ngreen vegetables, made prices favorable.\n$2.50a3.00; Georgia peaches, per crate, $1.00a\n1.50; ~antaloupes, per crate, $1.25a2 25; huckle\nberries, per gqt., T7alic: blackberries, per\nqt., salle; watermelons, 15adic.\nVegetabies\u2014 Potatoes, per bu., 75a%0c; new,\nper bbl, $8.00a4.00; cabbage, new, 30aslOc;\nkale, per bbl, 30alc; spinach, per bbl,\n#0ca$l.00; lettuce, per bbl., Toca$l.oo0; onions.\nBermuda, $1.25al.60; string beans, green, per\nbasket, \u00a7$1.00al.50; green peas, home grown,\nper bbl., $2.25a2.75; tomatoes, per crate, %ca\n1.50; beets, per bunch, 2ajc; rhubarb, per\nbunches, $1.00a2.25; asparagus, per doz,\noul2%3.00; cucumbers, per basket, 9Gca$l.Zs;\n_squush, per basket, 85ca$l 25; egg plant, per\ncrats, $.50a2.00; corn on cob, per crate, $1.2\nal.50.\nDressed Meats\u2014Crlvees, full dressed, 9alic:\nheads off, I0alle; ncz dressed calves, 6alc;\nhams, country, sw r cured, 1Zalic; hogs.\nsmall and neat, per cwt., T3paS%c; medium,\n7asc; heavy, Tc.\n\nLive Srock\u2014Cattle, extra, per cwt., $5.50a\n6.25; butcher, per cwt,, $4.50a5.00; commen,\nper cwi., $3.00a4.00; hogs, pe\u2019 cwt.,, gross,\n\u00a73.5085.75; ordinary, per. cwi., J.00a3.2%5; sheep,\nprime,  $3.00a4.00; lambs, spring. ic.\ncalves, prime, per 1b.. 7ail%c; medium, per\n1b... 6%:adc.\nACCUSED OFFICIAL\nIS DISCREDITED\nPITTSBURG, June 26. \u2014Investigation\ntoday of the story told by Frank P.\nMcCabe, superintendent of the oney\norder division of the Pittsburg post\noffice, who was arrested Wednesday\nfor the alleged embezzlement of $7,181,\nit is declared, has shown that no alarm\nof fire was turned in on any Sunday in\nJune, 1904.\n\nMcCabe claimed that during that\nmonth he had gone to the postoffice,\nand while watching fire engines pass,\nthieves had stolen more than $9,000 from\nhia desk.\n\u201cMaud graduated from your cooking\nschool last spring, didn't she?\u201d\n\u201cYes: but she\u2019s going to take a post\ngraduate course next fall.\u201d\n\u201cGoing back to the same school\nagain?\u2019\n\u201cUh, ne: =he's to he marriel to a\npoor young man. \u2014St. Louis Republic,\nTHE CURB MARKET.\nPRODUCE PRICES\nFINISHING COURSE.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, FRIDAY. JUNE 26. 1908.\nDEADLOCK UNBROKEN\nIN NORTH CAROLINA\nBitter Three-Cornered Fight\nfor Governor Continues\n\n\nUnabated.\nSRN bulley in Margaret Davie lo\nCHARLOTTE, N. C.. June 25.\u2014The\nthird day of the State Democratic con\nvention sees no decrease of bitterness\nin the three-cornered fight for gover\nnor.\nAt 10 o'clock a large crowd jammed\nthe hall, and at 0:30 Chairman Par\nsons had great dif iculty in getting or\nder.\nSupporters of lidtchin, Cralg, and\nHorne declare they wil] stay a week,\na month, or any indefinite time to se\ncure their man\u2019s nomination.\nThe convention at 11 o'clock proceeded\nwith the fifteenth ballot, amid cries of\n\u201cDoughton\u201d and \u201cDowd,\u201d from specta\ntors, and responding cries of \u201cNe dark\nhorse\u201d from the delegates.\nThe convention at 2 o'clock showed\nsymptoms of a coming break. On the\neighteenth ballot Northampton county\ncast her solid biock of ten votes for\nThomas W. Mason. The Auditorium is\nin a state of pandemonium, and it is\nexpected that the next two or three\nballats may nominate either Kitchin or\na dark horse.\nThe latest ballots were as follows:\nFifteenth ballot: Kitchin, 380; Craig,\n329: Horne, 147.\nSixteenth ballot: Kitchin, 386; Craig,\n327, Horne, 149.\nSeventeenth ballot: Kitchin, 382;\nCrag 331; Horne, 138.\nSOUTHERN RAILWAY\nDELAYS DISPUTE\noff CERig ue you\nNegotiations With Men Over\nWages Not to Be Resumed\nUntil! October.\nReferring to the negotiations which\nwere, April 1, 1908, suspended until June\n1, 1808, regarding wvages paid by South\nern Raiiway' Company and affiliated\nlines, President Finley, of the Southern\nRailway Compary, today said:\n\u201cIn view of the demonstrated greater\nefficiency of labor and its resuiting ben\nefits to the companies, and in the hope,\nand with some expectation, that pres\nent business conditions may show an\nimprovement, an understanding has\nbeen reached through Martin A. Knapp\nand Charles P. Neill, the mediators un\nder the Erdmann act, with all classes\nof employes that were parties to the\nsettlement of April 1, 158 that nego\ntiations temporarily suspended as of\nApril 1, 198, shall be further postponed\nuntil October 1, next, at which time\nsuch negotiations may be resumed at\nthe option of the companies through\nthe mediators under the Erdmann act.\u201d\nMRS. TAFT GUEST\nAT LUNCHEON TODAY\nShe and Son in New York to Meet\nWar Secretary\nTonight.\nNEW YORK, June 26. \u2014Mrs. William\nH. Taft, wife of the Presidential nom\ninee, and her son, Charles, arrived in\nNew York today from New Haven and\nwent to the Hotel Belmont, where they\nare guests at luncheon\u201d of John\nHays Hammond, who was a candidate\nfor nomination for Vice President at\nthe Republican convention.\nMrs. Taft said her husband would\nreach the city tonight and that they\nwould ge to the Hotel Manhattan, where\nthey wiil be the guest of J. Schmidlapp.\na wealthy Cincinnati man, and a dai\nrector of the Equitable Life Assurance\nSociety. She sald her husband would\ngo to Oyster Bay tomorrow for a con\nference with President Roosevelt.\n\u201cI do not fee! like talking politics,\u201d\nshe volunteered te the reporters, who\nmet her at the Grand Central station.\n#1 feel much fatigued from the com\nmencement exercises at Yale and the\nboat races of vesterday.\u201d\nFILES COMPLAINTS\nABOUT GRAIN RATES\nAlleging diserimination in favor of\nChicago on grain rates from Jowa,\nMinnesota, and South Dakota, the\nChamber of Commerce of Milwaukee to\nday filed two complaints with the Inter\nstate Commerce Commission against\nthe 1llinois Central Chicago, Milwaukee\nand St. Paul; Chicago and Northwest\nern, and the Chicago, Rock Island and\nPa ific railroads.\nThe complaints declare that the old\nthrough rate on grain was abolished\nAugust 1, 197, and the tariff \u201carbitrar\nily raised\u201d by making the through rate\nthe sum. of the local charges through\nChicago.\nVICTORY IS CERTAIN,\nSAYS LESLIE SHAW\nFormer Secretary of the Treasury\nLeslie M, Shaw came to Washington tos\nday on private business, but he lingered\nlong enough in the lobby of the Willard\nto say that the outlook for the Repub\nlicans in the coming campaign is un\nusually good.\n\u201cThe ticket is good, the platform is\ngood, and victory is certain,\u201d he said.\n\u201cWe will win and there will not be any\ndifficuity about it.\u201d\nBRYAN IS INDORSED\nBY IOWA CONVENTION\n\n\nSIOUX CITY, Iowa. June 26.\u2014The\nDemocratic State convention ended at\nL:45 yesterday afternoon with cheers\nfor William J. Bryan and the Jowa\nState ticket.\n\nIn the afternoon there was a fight\namong four judges for the nominations\nof judges of the sapreme couri. On a\nroll call vote of counties, D. W. Higbee,\not Creston, and Judge C. J. House,\nof Maquoketa, were the winners.\nThe platform expresses gratification\nover the prospect of the nomination of\nBryan for President; demands the elec\ntion of Senators by popular vote; de\nnounces \u2018\u2018government by \u2018njunction;\u201d\ndenounces prevailing freigi: rates as a\ndiscrimination against the people, and\n\u2018favors greater powers for the State\nrailway commission: demands enforce\nment of Jowa statutes against trusts\nand illegal combinations, and favors\nthe establishment of a State insurance\ncommission.\nThe State committee elected Lincoln\nPrice, of Indianola, chairman.\nOHIOAN WINS AT TRAPS.\nCOLUMBUS. Ohio, June 26.\u2014Fred\nHarlow, of Buckeye lake, Ohio, a\nmember of the Newark Gun Club, won\nthe Grand American Handicap for tra\nshooters at the Arlington grounds o!\nthe Columbus Gun Club today.\nHGH UP IN AIR\nSWINGS STEEPLEJACK\nDanger of the Man Whe\nWorks Between Heaven\nand Earth.\n\nfter a very adventurous life, during\nwhich I was a soldier, sailor, marine,\nand prizefighter, and traveled to nearly\nevery corner of the globe, 1 married and\nsettled down to the comparatively pro\nsaic life of a steeplejack.\nBeing very athletic and of muscular\nbuild, 1 found I could get plenty of em\nployment and good wages for painting\nflagpoles, chimney stacks, and similar\nwork that required steady nerves, the\nknack of rigging and a reaman\u2019s knowl\nedge of knots and hitches. There was\nan element of danger and daring about\nthis work that suited me, and I was\noften sent for by people at a distance\nwho had heard of me, and could get no\none locally who knew how, or had nerve\nencugh, to execute the jobs they placed\nin my nands.\nIn the fall of 1903 I took a contract to\nscrape and pamt the iron chimney stack\nof the Ridgewood pumping station,\nLong Island, N. Y., belonging to the\nBrooklyn water commissioners. The\nstack is the tallest iron chimney in the\nUnited States, being 275 feet Ligh. The\ndiameter of the stack is twelve feet at\nthe top and thirty-two feet at the\nground, and an outside iron ladder lead\ning to the top of the chimney is pro\nvided to facilitata any painting or re\npairs that may have to be done from\ntime to time. To do the work I built a\nlight swinging seaffold. Its middle fit\nted into the stack and it was swung\nfrom light half-inch tackles fitted at\neach end, suspended from two large\nhooks fixed at the top of the chimney\nexpressly for {he purpose.\nTo paint and scrape the stock all\naround I found I should have to move\nmy scaffold three times. 1 raised my\nstaging by means entirely alone except\nwhen it was necessary to haul the\nscaffold to the top of the stack, when\nI got one of the employes at the pump\ning station to work the falls, while 1\nran up the permanent ladder (ttached\nto the chimney to make the stag ng fast\nat the top. To lower the structure 1\nwould take off the hitch from one end\nat a time, and then lower both falls\ntcgeather.\nThe pumping station at Ridgewood is\nsituated In a very exposed position,\nand, as it was the month of December\nand very windy, to keep from beins\nblown out from the chimney I had a\nrope attached to one end of the scaf\nfold, passed around the stack, and made\nfast to the other end.\nOne day I was scraping the loose\nscales of paint off the iron plates, and\nhad descended about half way Gown the\nchimney. I was working very hard t\u00ab\nget finished, when [I was suddenly\nawakened to the fact that it was grow\ning dark\u00ae but, as I requirea very littl\nlight for the job in hand, I continued\n\u2018my scrapin The wind was howling\naround the chimney, and seemed to be\nir creasing in volume, thoush I paid bu\nlittle attention to it.\nClose to Death.\n1 worked until rearly o'clock. when\nft became very dark, so I decided 0\npull my \u2018seaffold around to the ladder\non the opposite side of the chimney.\nwake fast. and go home. I was about\nto put this plan into operation when\ndisaster overctook me. As 1 unfasten\ned the rope which held my stage to the\nchimney, intending te pull the seafiold\nreund to the ladder, it slipped from\nmy fingers and vanished into the night.\nHardly had 1 realized what had kap\npened than the high wind, catching the\nlong line of ropes ard falls of my tac\nkle, blew the scaffold, with me upon\nit. out and away from the stack to a\ndistance of twenty feet. Then, the\nforce of the gust suddenly abating I\nswung in with a fearful crash agamst\nthe chimney.\nThe shock of the collision nearly flung\nme from the stage. but. although dazed.\nI vet clung on for dear life. Another\ninstant and 1 was carried out again,\nwhirled around and set hurtling ints\nthe chimney again by another puff of\nwind.\nBreathless and terror-stricken, I hung\nTOMORROW\nwe Offer You the Biggest Bargains\nof the Year in Clothing i\nAll of our $15, S18 and $520 All of the Chil dren's Suits\nCaroag 1 hibet and Clay Dk ig- th ai 14 D\nil\nOCTLLD, 1 t dllU til SOW FSS\nonal Suits; the newest shades Tomonow OEE $2. 48\nof brown and other TTT\nstvlish colors. $9.75 SPECIAL--Men\u2019s SQU ARE\na DEAL Hosiery; six pairs guar-\nTwo hundred Men's Twe- anteed six months\npiece Suits, worth Or New stockings. x 50\nto *12 \u201choice\nap fo $12 Choice 8 AB ers Fancy Balbrigan Un\nderwear; the Kind\nOne lot of Men's Crash that always sell for I\"\nSuits, sizes 34, 35 30\u00a2. 1 OMOTTOW C\n24 an 37. Tomor- TT\nol 37 